Question 1

Generate three sets of 20 observation with their respective mean shift (60 total). 50 variables.

num_classes <- 3
variables <- 50
obs <- 20
set.seed(2394)
total_obs <- obs * num_classes
x <- matrix(rnorm(num_classes*variables*obs), ncol = variables)
mean_shift <- sample(-10:10, obs, replace = FALSE)
for (var in 1:variables) {
  for (c in 0:(num_classes - 1)) {
    l<-(c * obs):((c + 1) * obs)
    x[l, var] <- x[l, var]+ mean_shift[c+1]
  }
}

Question 2)

Perform k-means

pr.out <- prcomp(x)
biplot(pr.out, scale = 0  )

Question 3)

k-means -> k=3

km.out <- kmeans(x, 3, nstart = 20)
plot(x, col = (km.out$cluster + 1), main = paste0("K-Means Clustering Results
with K=", num_classes, ' and mean shifts: ', paste(mean_shift, collapse = ', ')), xlab = "", ylab = "", pch = 20, cex = 2)

k-means -> k=3 Three distinct clusters were found. This indicates that there are were three principle components required to represent the data we generated. This is inline with the truth as we created the data with three distinct mean shifts.
